english:
  title: Inscription for the Great Bell with Preface
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the third year since Joseon received the Mandate of Heaven, the capital was established on the northern banks of the Han River. The following year, construction of the palace began in earnest. That summer, the court commissioned the casting of a great bell. When it was completed, a bell tower was erected in the great marketplace to suspend it there—thus preserving our new achievements and transmitting our glorious legacy to posterity.

    Since ancient times, those who have founded nations and established great undertakings have inscribed their accomplishments upon bells and tripods. The resonant voices of these bells reverberate through the ears and hearts of future generations. In the great cities of the realm, the bell is struck at dawn and dusk to mark the rhythm of the people's labor and rest. Thus the bell serves a noble purpose indeed.

    Our Lord, even during his years in the shadow, grew daily in virtue and esteem. Heaven's mandate and the people's hearts naturally flowed toward him—a tide impossible to resist. The worthy ministers gave their counsel and strength unstintingly. In a single day, he supplanted the House of Koryo and took possession of the realm. Day and night he labored in thought, establishing principles and ordering the realm, laying the foundation for ten thousand generations of peace. Thus can it be said that he has accomplished great deeds and established lasting order. This deserves to be inscribed upon the bell for all ages to behold.

    Moreover, the *Book of Changes* teaches: "The great virtue of Heaven and Earth is Life. The great treasure of the Sage is Position. What preserves Position? Humanity alone." This means the Sage takes the life-giving heart of Heaven and Earth as his own heart and extends it without measure, thus preserving his rightful place. Though Heaven and humanity differ in station, their hearts are one.

    When our Lord ascended the throne, not a drop of blood was shed. Within and without, all was peaceful. Those people who had suffered under cruel rule now know the joy of living. Such is the virtue of loving life—even the great Sage-King Shun could not surpass it. Surely this must be inscribed.

    The Inscription:

    Ah, majestic is our Lord,
    Receiver of Heaven's broad Mandate,
    Who came to build this new capital
    On the northern banks of the Han.

    Once stood ancient Songdo,
    Where the state grew ever weaker.
    Our Lord came to transform it,
    Replacing tyranny with virtue.

    The people witnessed no warfare,
    All under Heaven grew clear and bright.
    Wise men offered their strength,
    And Great Peace was achieved.

    From distant lands, all gathered near,
    Population flourished and multiplied.
    Then was this great bell cast,
    Its voice echoing morning and night.

    Our Lord's merit and glory—
    Engraved and preserved forever here,
    Guarding over this sacred city,
    For ten thousand years to come.
  footnotes:
    - The preface employs the classical concept of the Mandate of Heaven (天命) to legitimize the Joseon dynasty's founding, a key ideological framework in East Asian political thought.
    - The reference to the *Book of Changes* (《周易》) serves to ground the new regime's moral authority in Confucian philosophical principles, particularly the virtue of *ren* (仁, humanity/benevolence).
    - The casting of the great bell was not merely a ceremonial act but served the practical function of regulating public time and labor in the capital, symbolizing both order and benevolence.
    - Songdo (松都) refers to Gaeseong, the ancient capital of Koryo that Joseon replaced.
